    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Complete Document List -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Documents Required for Family Visa Sponsorship</h2>
      <p>GDRFA requires specific documents depending on who you are sponsoring. Here is the full list, sorted by document source.</p>

      <h3>Sponsor's Documents (Already in UAE)</h3>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Valid passport</strong> with UAE residence visa (minimum 6 months validity)</li>
        <li><strong>Emirates ID</strong> — both sides</li>
        <li><strong>Salary certificate</strong> from employer — must show minimum AED 4,000 (or AED 3,000 plus accommodation). Must be in Arabic or <a href="/legal-translation-dubai/">translated to Arabic</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Tenancy contract</strong> (Ejari) — proving adequate accommodation</li>
        <li><strong>Passport-size photographs</strong> — white background, recent</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Spouse Visa Documents (From Home Country)</h3>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong><a href="/personal/vital-records/marriage/">Marriage certificate</a></strong> — original, attested and translated to Arabic</li>
        <li><strong>Spouse's passport</strong> — valid for minimum 6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Spouse's passport photographs</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Child Visa Documents (Per Child)</h3>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong><a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">Birth certificate</a></strong> — original, attested and translated to Arabic</li>
        <li><strong>Child's passport</strong> — valid for minimum 6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Child's passport photographs</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Parent Sponsorship (Additional Requirements)</h3>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li><strong>Minimum salary of AED 20,000</strong> (higher threshold than spouse/child)</li>
        <li><strong>Two-bedroom accommodation</strong> minimum</li>
        <li><strong>Birth certificate</strong> proving parent-child relationship — attested and translated</li>
        <li><strong>Health insurance</strong> for each parent</li>
        <li><strong>Medical fitness certificate</strong> after arrival</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-block callout-block--warning">
        <h4>Documents That Do NOT Need Translation</h4>
        <p>Emirates ID, UAE-issued tenancy contracts (Ejari), and documents already in Arabic do not require translation. Your <a href="/resources/translation-type-decision-guide/">translation type decision guide</a> helps determine exactly what needs translating.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The 6-Step Sequence -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>The 6-Step Document Sequence</h2>
      <p>This is the exact order. Getting any step out of sequence means going back and starting over.</p>

      <div class="sequence-steps">
        <div class="sequence-step">
          <div class="step-number">1</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Obtain Original Documents From Home Country</h3>
            <p>GDRFA requires original documents, not certified copies. If your <a href="/personal/vital-records/marriage/">marriage certificate</a> or <a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">birth certificate</a> is with your family back home, they need to send the original.</p>
            <p>For countries that issue multiple originals (like India), one original is sufficient. For countries that issue a single original, check if your home country's civil registry can issue a certified duplicate.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sequence-step">
          <div class="step-number">2</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Authenticate in Your Home Country</h3>
            <p>The authentication path depends on whether your country is a <a href="/services/attestation/">Hague Convention member</a>.</p>

            <div class="path-comparison">
              <div class="path-card">
                <h4>Hague Convention Countries</h4>
                <p class="path-label">India, USA, UK, Canada, Philippines, Bangladesh</p>
                <ol>
                  <li>Notarize the document</li>
                  <li>Get apostille from competent authority</li>
                </ol>
                <p class="path-note">Apostille replaces the embassy chain. Faster and cheaper.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="path-card">
                <h4>Non-Hague Countries</h4>
                <p class="path-label">Pakistan, Egypt, Syria, Jordan</p>
                <ol>
                  <li>Authenticate through home country ministry</li>
                  <li>Attest at home country MOFA</li>
                  <li>Attest at UAE Embassy in your home country</li>
                </ol>
                <p class="path-note">Full chain adds 1-2 weeks compared to Hague countries.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sequence-step">
          <div class="step-number">3</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>UAE MOFA Attestation</h3>
            <p>All foreign documents — whether apostilled or embassy-attested — must pass through <a href="/services/attestation/">UAE MOFA attestation</a>. This step validates the foreign authentication for use in UAE government systems.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>System:</strong> eDAS 2.0 (digital attestation)</li>
              <li><strong>Cost:</strong> AED 150 per document</li>
              <li><strong>Timeline:</strong> 1-3 working days</li>
            </ul>
            <p>MOFA adds stickers and stamps to your documents. These marks are critical — they must appear in your Arabic translation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sequence-step">
          <div class="step-number">4</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>MOJ-Certified Arabic Translation</h3>
            <p>After attestation is complete, have your documents translated into Arabic by an <a href="/legal-translation-dubai/">MOJ-certified translator</a>. This step MUST come after attestation, not before.</p>
            <div class="callout-block callout-block--danger">
              <h4>The Most Expensive Mistake</h4>
              <p>If you translate before attesting, your translation will not include the MOFA attestation stamps and stickers. GDRFA will reject the application. You will need to pay for a complete retranslation after attestation. We see this mistake regularly.</p>
            </div>
            <p>Documents that need Arabic translation for family visa:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/personal/vital-records/marriage/">Marriage certificate</a></li>
              <li><a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">Birth certificates</a> (for each child)</li>
              <li>Salary certificate (if not already in Arabic)</li>
              <li><a href="/personal/immigration/pcc/">Police clearance certificate</a> (if required)</li>
              <li>Any other document not originally in Arabic</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Standard translation takes 24 hours. Express service delivers in 2-4 hours. Send documents via <a href="https://wa.me/971508620217">WhatsApp</a> and we confirm which ones need translation before you pay.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sequence-step">
          <div class="step-number">5</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Typing Center Submission</h3>
            <p>You cannot submit directly to GDRFA. Family visa applications go through approved typing centers that enter your data into the GDRFA system.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Dubai:</strong> Approximately 600 GDRFA-approved typing centers</li>
              <li><strong>Location clusters:</strong> Near government offices, International City, Karama, Deira, Al Nahda</li>
              <li><strong>What they do:</strong> Enter all data from your documents into the GDRFA portal, upload scanned copies, and submit the application</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Bring all original documents plus their Arabic translations. The typing center will need both. Some centers also handle the application fee payment (currently AED 300 for the entry permit).</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sequence-step">
          <div class="step-number">6</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>GDRFA Review and Entry Permit</h3>
            <p>After the typing center submits your application, GDRFA reviews it electronically. You can track status through the GDRFA portal, app, or Amer service centers.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Approval timeline:</strong> 3-7 working days (varies)</li>
              <li><strong>Entry permit:</strong> Issued via email and SMS</li>
              <li><strong>Entry permit validity:</strong> 60 days from issue (your family must enter UAE within this period)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Once your family arrives, they must complete medical fitness, Emirates ID registration, and visa stamping within 60 days of entry.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Common Rejections -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Why GDRFA Rejects Family Visa Applications</h2>
      <p>GDRFA rejection notices are mostly generic. You receive a "Rejected" status with limited explanation. Based on what we see from clients who come to us after rejection, these are the most common causes.</p>

      <div class="rejection-list">
        <div class="rejection-item">
          <div class="rejection-icon"><i class="fas fa-arrows-rotate"></i></div>
          <div class="rejection-content">
            <h3>Wrong Sequence: Translated Before Attesting</h3>
            <p>The translation does not include MOFA attestation marks. GDRFA cannot verify the document's authenticity chain. You need a complete retranslation after proper attestation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <div class="rejection-icon"><i class="fas fa-language"></i></div>
          <div class="rejection-content">
            <h3>Documents Not in Arabic</h3>
            <p>All foreign-language documents must be in Arabic. English-only submissions are rejected. Even if the typing center accepts them, GDRFA reviewers will flag the missing translations.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <div class="rejection-icon"><i class="fas fa-stamp"></i></div>
          <div class="rejection-content">
            <h3>Missing or Incomplete Attestation</h3>
            <p>Skipping MOFA attestation — or skipping a step in the attestation chain — results in rejection. Each step in the chain validates the previous one. A missing link breaks the entire chain.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <div class="rejection-icon"><i class="fas fa-id-card"></i></div>
          <div class="rejection-content">
            <h3>Non-MOJ-Certified Translation</h3>
            <p>Only translations by MOJ-licensed translators are accepted. Translations from non-licensed translators, even if accurate, lack the required MOJ stamp and QR verification.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <div class="rejection-icon"><i class="fas fa-calendar-xmark"></i></div>
          <div class="rejection-content">
            <h3>Expired or Stale Documents</h3>
            <p>Salary certificates older than 30 days may be rejected. Passports with less than 6 months validity are automatically flagged. Some typing centers will not even accept expired documents.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <div class="rejection-icon"><i class="fas fa-user-slash"></i></div>
          <div class="rejection-content">
            <h3>Name Mismatches Across Documents</h3>
            <p>If your name appears differently on your passport, marriage certificate, and birth certificate, GDRFA may flag the discrepancy. This is common with transliterated names from Arabic, Hindi, or Urdu. Your translator should note these variations.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>For detailed rejection patterns and how to fix them, read our <a href="/blog/gdrfa-visa-document-problems/">GDRFA visa rejection prevention guide</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Country-Specific Attestation -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Attestation Chains by Country</h2>
      <p>The <a href="/services/attestation/">attestation process</a> varies significantly by country. Here are the most common nationalities and their specific chains for family visa documents.</p>

      <table class="attestation-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Country</th>
            <th>Hague?</th>
            <th>Attestation Chain</th>
            <th>Typical Time</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>India</strong></td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>SDM/Notary &rarr; MEA Apostille &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>5-7 days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Pakistan</strong></td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>IBCC/HEC &rarr; Pak MOFA &rarr; UAE Embassy &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>10-14 days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Philippines</strong></td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>PSA/DFA &rarr; Apostille &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>5-7 days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Bangladesh</strong></td>
            <td>Yes (2025)</td>
            <td>Ministry &rarr; Apostille &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>5-10 days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Egypt</strong></td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Ministry &rarr; Egypt MOFA &rarr; UAE Embassy &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>10-14 days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>UK</strong></td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Solicitor &rarr; FCDO Apostille &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>5-7 days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>USA</strong></td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Notary &rarr; Secretary of State Apostille &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>5-10 days</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Canada</strong></td>
            <td>Yes (2024)</td>
            <td>Notary &rarr; GAC Apostille &rarr; UAE MOFA</td>
            <td>5-10 days</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="callout-block callout-block--info">
        <h4>UAE Is Not a Hague Convention Member</h4>
        <p>Even when your home country has the Hague apostille, the final UAE MOFA attestation step is always required. The apostille simplifies the process in your home country, but it does not eliminate UAE-side attestation. <a href="/services/attestation/">Learn more about the attestation process</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Realistic Timeline -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>Realistic Timeline: Start to Entry Permit</h2>
      <p>Here is what the full process actually looks like, assuming no rejections.</p>

      <div class="timeline-breakdown">
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Home country attestation</div>
          <div class="timeline-hague">
            <span class="timeline-label">Hague</span>
            <span class="timeline-duration">3-5 days</span>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-nonhague">
            <span class="timeline-label">Non-Hague</span>
            <span class="timeline-duration">7-14 days</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-phase">UAE MOFA attestation</div>
          <div class="timeline-hague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">1-3 days</span>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-nonhague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">1-3 days</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Arabic translation</div>
          <div class="timeline-hague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">1 day (express: 2-4 hrs)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-nonhague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">1 day (express: 2-4 hrs)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Typing center + GDRFA review</div>
          <div class="timeline-hague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">3-7 days</span>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-nonhague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">3-7 days</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-row timeline-row--total">
          <div class="timeline-phase">Total</div>
          <div class="timeline-hague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">8-16 days</span>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-nonhague">
            <span class="timeline-duration">12-25 days</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>These timelines assume documents are ready and correct. A rejection adds 1-4 weeks depending on what needs to be fixed. The single best way to avoid delays: get the attestation-translation sequence right the first time.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- After Approval -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container container--narrow">
      <h2>After the Entry Permit: What Comes Next</h2>
      <p>The entry permit is not the end. Once your family member arrives in the UAE, they have 60 days to complete these steps.</p>

      <div class="after-steps">
        <div class="after-step">
          <span class="after-step-num">1</span>
